2026-05-30 | Replace Each Element with XOR of Adjacent Elements

	Question
Modify the array in-place according to the rules.
	Key Insight
If we directly modify arr,
later computations will use already-updated values,
which is incorrect.
So:
		first store original array in a copy.
Then compute all new values using the copy.
	Approach
1.	Create a copy of the original array.
2.	Update first element:
		copy[0] ^ copy[1]
3.	Update middle elements:
		copy[i-1] ^ copy[i+1]
4.	Update last element:
		copy[n-2] ^ copy[n-1]
5.	Write results back into arr.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    void updateArray(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        if(n == 1)
            return;
        vector<int> temp = arr;
        arr[0] = temp[0] ^ temp[1];
        for(int i = 1; i < n - 1; i++){
            arr[i] = temp[i - 1] ^ temp[i + 1];
        }
        arr[n - 1] = temp[n - 2] ^ temp[n - 1];
    }
};
	Key Insight
All replacements must use the original array values, not the already modified ones. Therefore, keeping a copy of the original array is necessary before performing updates.
